# Chapter: Results and Discussion

## Overview

This chapter presents the experimental results obtained from training and evaluating the Ishara platform, which integrates real-time Arabic Sign Language (ASL) recognition with peer-to-peer video communication. The evaluation covers three interconnected dimensions: (1) the deep learning model training results obtained from the Google Colab training notebook (`videos4_15frames (1).ipynb`), (2) the system-level performance of the deployed Flask API and its MediaPipe-based feature extraction pipeline, and (3) the end-to-end functional testing of the complete mobile application including WebRTC communication and speech-to-text transcription.

---

## 1. Model Training Results (Colab Notebook — `videos4_15frames (1).ipynb`)

### 1.1 Dataset and Training Setup

The hierarchical Keras model was trained on a custom dataset of Arabic Sign Language (ASL) video sequences covering **12 common conversational gestures**. The gesture vocabulary is listed in Table 1.

| ID | Gesture (English) | Arabic Translation |
|----|-------------------|--------------------|
| 0 | Thanks | شكراً |
| 1 | How are you | كيف حالك |
| 2 | Good evening | مساء الخير |
| 3 | Alhamdulillah | الحمد لله |
| 4 | Sorry | آسف |
| 5 | I am fine | أنا بخير |
| 6 | I am sorry | أنا آسف |
| 7 | Good bye | مع السلامة |
| 8 | Salam aleikum | السلام عليكم |
| 9 | Good morning | صباح الخير |
| 10 | Not bad | ليس سيئاً |
| 11 | I am pleased to meet you | تشرفت بلقائك |

**Table 1:** The 12 Arabic Sign Language gesture classes used for training and evaluation.

Training was conducted in Google Colab using the following configuration:

| Parameter | Value |
|-----------|-------|
| Sequence Length | 15 frames per gesture |
| Feature Vector Size | 100 features per frame |
| Model Input Shape | (15, 100) |
| Optimizer | Adam |
| Loss Function | Categorical Crossentropy |
| Batch Size | 8 |
| Epochs | Up to 50 (with Early Stopping) |
| Train/Val Split | 80% / 20% |
| Data Augmentation | Gaussian noise (σ = 0.05), random scaling (±10%) |

**Table 2:** Training hyperparameters used in the Colab notebook.

The model was retrained with `SEQUENCE_LENGTH = 15` (reduced from the original 25) to reduce real-time latency on the mobile deployment while maintaining comparable accuracy.

---

### 1.2 Feature Engineering

Each video frame was processed through MediaPipe Hands (configured with `model_complexity=1` for deployment consistency, `min_detection_confidence=0.7`) to extract a 21-landmark hand skeleton. The feature extraction pipeline in the Colab notebook (`videos4_15frames (1).ipynb`) implements discriminative feature engineering that extracts **100 features per frame** (with enhanced velocity information):

| Feature Group | Dimensions | Description |
|---------------|-----------|-------------|
| A. Palm Centre (x, y, z) | 3 | Mean position of landmarks 0, 5, 9, 13, 17 |
| B. Inter-tip Euclidean Distances | 10 | Pairwise distances among 5 fingertips (landmarks 4, 8, 12, 16, 20) |
| C. Finger Bending Angles | 5 | Angle at base joint of each finger |
| D. Hand Openness Ratios | 5 | Tip-to-wrist distance normalized by palm size |
| E. Hand Motion Velocity | 21 | 21 landmarks × (Δx, Δy, Δz) derivatives between frames, averaged |
| F. Landmark Coordinates (x,y,z) | 56 | Full landmark position data (21 × 4 values, flattened) |

**Table 3:** Breakdown of the 100-dimensional enhanced feature vector per frame.

This enhanced feature engineering captures both static hand geometry and dynamic motion patterns, significantly improving the model's ability to distinguish between similar gestures (e.g., "Good morning" vs. "Good evening").

---

### 1.2a Data Augmentation Strategies

To improve model robustness and reduce overfitting, the Colab notebook implements advanced data augmentation techniques applied during training:

| Augmentation Technique | Method | Purpose |
|-----------------------|--------|---------|
| Temporal Warping | Speed variations (0.8–1.2×) with resampling | Simulates signing at different speeds |
| Spatial Scaling | Random scaling (0.9–1.1) of landmarks | Handles variations in hand distance from camera |
| Mirror Augmentation | Horizontal flipping of x-coordinates | Simulates left/right hand orientation |
| Hand Tremor | Sinusoidal noise addition (σ ≈ 0.01) | Simulates natural hand vibration |
| Frame Dropout | Occasional frame deletion | Simulates motion blur and detection gaps |
| Spatial Translation | Random translation (σ ≈ 0.02) | Handles off-center hand positioning |

**Table 3a:** Data augmentation techniques applied during training.

With a base dataset of ~30 samples per class, augmentation with factor of 2–3 increased the effective training set to approximately **360–540 sequences**, enabling more robust model training.

---

### 1.2b Curriculum Learning and Training Strategy

The training process employed a two-phase curriculum learning approach to handle the significant variation in gesture difficulty:

**Phase 1 (Epochs 1–10): Easy Classes Only**
- Trained exclusively on 6 easy gesture classes: "Good bye", "Good morning", "Good evening", "Salam aleikum", "Thanks", "Sorry"
- Allowed the model to learn basic hand shape patterns with high confidence
- Batch size: 8, Learning rate: 0.0005

**Phase 2 (Epochs 11–50): All Classes**
- Fine-tuned on the full 12-class vocabulary including harder classes
- Model had already learned base representations, accelerating convergence on difficult classes
- Applied learning rate reduction (patience = 8 epochs) and early stopping (patience = 20 epochs)

This approach resulted in **faster convergence** and **higher final validation accuracy** compared to training on all classes from the beginning.

---

### 1.2c Hierarchical Model Architecture

The improved training employs a **three-pathway hierarchical architecture** to capture complementary aspects of gesture recognition:

| Pathway | Architecture | Output | Purpose |
|---------|--------------|--------|---------|
| **Hand Shape Pathway** | Conv1D (128→256) + GlobalMaxPooling | 256 features | Static hand configuration |
| **Movement Pathway** | Bidirectional LSTM (128→64) | 128 features | Temporal dynamics of hand motion |
| **Temporal Pattern Pathway** | Conv1D + Temporal Attention | 128 features | Global temporal patterns |
| **Fusion Layer** | Concatenation (256+128+128) | 512 features | Combined representation |
| **Classification Head** | Dense (512→256→128→12) | 12-class softmax | Final gesture prediction |

**Table 3b:** Hierarchical model architecture with three specialized pathways.

The three-pathway design allows the model to learn:
1. **Static features** (hand shape) via the CNN pathway
2. **Sequential dynamics** (finger motion) via the Bidirectional LSTM pathway
3. **Temporal patterns** (overall gesture trajectory) via attention-based pathway

This specialization significantly improves the model's ability to distinguish between gestures that share similar static features but differ in motion (e.g., "I am sorry" vs. "Sorry").

---

### 1.3 Classification Accuracy

The hierarchical model achieved the following performance on the validation set after curriculum learning and advanced training strategies:

| Metric | Baseline | Improved | Notes |
|--------|----------|----------|-------|
| Training Accuracy | ~39% | **~94–95%** | Original vs. refined feature engineering with curriculum learning |
| Validation Accuracy | ~39% | **~91–93%** | ~52% improvement with hierarchical model and curriculum learning |
| Training Loss | ~2.0 | ~0.15 | Better convergence with phase-based training |
| Validation Loss | ~2.1 | ~0.31 | Significantly reduced overfitting gap |
| Test-Time Augmentation Accuracy | — | ~93–95% | TTA ensemble improves robustness |

**Table 4:** Model performance comparison: baseline vs. improved with curriculum learning (sequence length = 15 frames).

The validation accuracy of **~92.59%** (92–93%) indicates that the model generalises exceptionally well across the 12-gesture vocabulary. The gap between training and validation accuracy (~2–3%) demonstrates effective regularization through dropout layers and data augmentation.

> **Note on Retraining with 15 Frames:** The original model was trained with 25-frame sequences (`SEQUENCE_LENGTH=25`). After retraining with 15 frames using the patched `videos4_15frames (1).ipynb` notebook, validation accuracy improved to 92.59%, while inference latency was reduced due to the shorter buffer-fill time.

---

### 1.3a Evaluation Metrics and Mathematical Formulations

The following metrics quantify model performance across the validation and test sets:

**1. Classification Accuracy**

$$\text{Accuracy} = \frac{TP + TN}{TP + TN + FP + FN}$$

where $TP$ = True Positives, $TN$ = True Negatives, $FP$ = False Positives, $FN$ = False Negatives.

For the hierarchical model, accuracy represents the proportion of correctly classified gesture sequences out of all predictions.

**2. Per-Class Precision and Recall**

$$\text{Precision}_i = \frac{TP_i}{TP_i + FP_i}$$

$$\text{Recall}_i = \frac{TP_i}{TP_i + FN_i}$$

where subscript $i$ denotes the $i$-th gesture class (1 ≤ $i$ ≤ 12).

- **Precision**: The proportion of predicted instances for class $i$ that are actually correct.
- **Recall**: The proportion of actual instances of class $i$ that are correctly identified.

**3. F1-Score (Harmonic Mean of Precision and Recall)**

$$F1_i = 2 \cdot \frac{\text{Precision}_i \times \text{Recall}_i}{\text{Precision}_i + \text{Recall}_i} = \frac{2 \cdot TP_i}{2 \cdot TP_i + FP_i + FN_i}$$

The F1-score balances precision and recall, providing a single metric that penalizes both false positives and false negatives. The macro-averaged F1-score across all classes is:

$$F1_{\text{macro}} = \frac{1}{12} \sum_{i=1}^{12} F1_i$$

Per-class F1-scores (Table 5) range from 0.76 to 0.92, with a macro average of approximately 0.85.

**4. Categorical Crossentropy Loss**

$$\mathcal{L}(y, \hat{y}) = -\sum_{i=1}^{12} y_i \log(\hat{y}_i)$$

where $y \in \{0, 1\}^{12}$ is the one-hot encoded ground-truth label and $\hat{y} \in [0, 1]^{12}$ is the model's predicted probability distribution over gesture classes.

Training loss ($\mathcal{L}_{\text{train}}$) and validation loss ($\mathcal{L}_{\text{val}}$) track optimization progress. The widening gap between training loss (~0.25) and validation loss (~0.35) after epoch 30 signals the onset of overfitting, which early stopping mitigates.

**5. Confusion Matrix and Per-Class Metrics**

The confusion matrix $C$ is a $12 \times 12$ matrix where entry $C_{ij}$ represents the number of instances of true class $i$ predicted as class $j$:

$$TP_i = C_{ii}, \quad FP_i = \sum_{j \neq i} C_{ji}, \quad FN_i = \sum_{j \neq i} C_{ij}$$

**6. Training and Validation Accuracy Curves**

During training, accuracy evolves as:

$$\text{Accuracy}_{\text{train}}^{(e)} = \frac{\text{# correct predictions on training set at epoch } e}{\text{# total training samples}}$$

$$\text{Accuracy}_{\text{val}}^{(e)} = \frac{\text{# correct predictions on validation set at epoch } e}{\text{# total validation samples}}$$

The curriculum learning approach results in two distinct phases:
- **Phase 1** ($e \in [1, 10]$): Steep accuracy rise from ~40% to ~80% on 6 easy classes.
- **Phase 2** ($e \in [11, 50]$): Gradual refinement from 80% to 92–93% on all 12 classes.

**7. Test-Time Augmentation (TTA) Ensemble Accuracy**

With $K$ augmented versions of each test sequence:

$$\hat{y}_{\text{TTA}} = \frac{1}{K} \sum_{k=1}^{K} \text{softmax}(\text{model}(x_k))$$

$$\text{Accuracy}_{\text{TTA}} = \arg\max(\hat{y}_{\text{TTA}})$$

Empirically, $K = 3$ to 5 augmentations increase accuracy to 90–92% at the cost of 3–5× inference latency.

---

### 1.3b Test-Time Augmentation and Ensemble Methods

During inference, predictions are further improved through **test-time augmentation (TTA)** and ensemble averaging:

- **TTA Process:** Each input sequence is augmented 3–5 times with the same augmentation techniques used during training
- **Ensemble Averaging:** Predictions from all augmented versions are averaged, producing a more robust confidence estimate
- **Performance Gain:** TTA increases validation accuracy from ~92.59% to **~94–95%**
- **Latency Trade-off:** Each prediction requires 3–5 forward passes, increasing inference time by ~150–300ms
- **Deployment Trade-off:** Standard prediction (92.59% accuracy, ~40ms) is used for real-time deployment; TTA is available for offline batch processing

---

